'''Kisshō-in Tamon-ji''' (吉祥院多聞寺) is a {{ill|Shingon Buddhism|ja|真言宗|12=draft|12=draft}} temple located in {{ill|Arino-chō, Karato|ja|有野町唐櫃|12=draft|12=draft}}, {{ill|Kita-ku, Kobe|ja|北区|12=draft|12=draft}}, {{ill|Hyōgo Prefecture|ja|兵庫県|12=draft|12=draft}}. The mountain name is Mount Rokkō (六甲山). The principal image of worship is the secret {{ill|Vaiśravaṇa|ja|毘沙門天|12=draft|12=draft}}, along with {{ill|Kisshōten|ja|吉祥天|12=draft|12=draft}} and Zen-ni-shidōji (善弐師童子).

== History ==
According to tradition, the temple was founded by the Indian monk {{ill|Hōdō|lt=Hōdō-sennin|ja|法道仙人|12=draft|12=draft}} during the reign of {{ill|Emperor Kōtoku|ja|孝徳天皇|12=draft|12=draft}}. It was later restored in 858 CE by the Kōyasan monk Chōzen Ajari. Originally, the temple structures were located southeast of the current site on {{ill|Kotera-yama|ja|古寺山|12=draft|12=draft}}.

In 1180 CE, during {{ill|Taira no Kiyomori|ja|Taira no Kiyomori|12=draft|12=draft}}’s relocation of the capital to Fukuhara (modern-day Kobe), the temple was designated to guard the northeastern direction of the city, akin to Kyoto’s {{ill|Mount Kurama|ja|鞍馬山|12=draft|12=draft}}. Taira no Kiyomori endowed the temple with vast landholdings and relocated people from {{ill|Kurama|ja|鞍馬|12=draft|12=draft}}, {{ill|Yase|ja|八瀬|12=draft|12=draft}}, and {{ill|Ōhara, Kyoto|ja|大原|12=draft|12=draft}}, leaving the Karato region with unique customs that persisted into modern times.

During the {{ill|Genpei War|ja|治承・寿永の乱|12=draft|12=draft}}, the temple was burned down by {{ill|Minamoto no Yoshitsune|ja|源義経|12=draft|12=draft}} for refusing to assist in his attack on Ichi-no-Tani. The temple was later rebuilt in 1462 at its present location. The current main hall was reconstructed in 1690 by the monk Ryōen.

The temple once hosted a grand annual “Otō Festival” on February 11. The {{ill|Karato Village|ja|唐櫃村|12=draft|12=draft}} was historically managed by the {{ill|Shiki family|ja|四鬼家|12=draft|12=draft}}, who were said to have migrated from {{ill|Tenkawa, Nara|ja|天川村|12=draft|12=draft}}, under the command of {{ill|En no Gyōja|ja|役行者|12=draft|12=draft}}. They managed the village and the western Rokkō mountains, overseeing the activities of Rokkō Shugendō practitioners.

== Oku-no-in of Tamon-ji ==
[[File:Rokkohime shrine, Kobe 003.jpg|right|thumb|150px|Rokkō Hime Shrine]]
The Oku-no-in (inner sanctuary) is located along Mount Rokkō’s ridgeline near {{ill|Gyōgai-iwa|ja|仰臥岩|12=draft|12=draft}}, {{ill|Un-ga-iwa|ja|雲ヶ岩|12=draft|12=draft}}, and {{ill|Rokkō Hime Shrine|ja|六甲比命神社|12=draft|12=draft}} (dedicated to {{ill|Benzaiten|ja|弁財天|12=draft|12=draft}}). According to legend, Hōdō-sennin encountered {{ill|Vaiśravaṇa|ja|毘沙門天|12=draft|12=draft}} here, descending on purple clouds during his ascetic training.
== See Also ==
* {{ill|Rokkō Hime Daizen Shrine|ja|六甲比命神社|12=draft|12=draft}}
* {{ill|Hōdō|ja|法道仙人|12=draft|12=draft}}
* {{ill|Shiki family|ja|四鬼氏|12=draft|12=draft}}
* {{ill|Rokkō Shugendō|ja|六甲修験|12=draft|12=draft}}<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20131219044244/http://www.geocities.jp/jyunkubo/kobe/hike_sub/roko_shugen/roko_shugenroute.htm Overview of Rokkō Shugendō]</ref>

